<paragraph blockId="1.[856,1499,183,488]" pageId="1" pageNumber="173">The UPS-THUNB No. 8139 sheet bears no locality details, but it clearly comprises one of Thunberg’s collections from Japan.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[856,1499,183,488]" lastBlockId="2.[123,766,183,644]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="174" pageId="1" pageNumber="173">
The above conclusion is based on the specimen having upward oriented (i.e., “corollis erectis”) flowers and lanceo- late leaves (i.e., “Foliis … lanceolatis”). This probably misled Thunberg attributing 
<taxonomicName box="[1080,1276,339,363]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Lilium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bulbliferum">
<emphasis box="[1080,1276,339,363]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="173">Lilium bulbliferum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to UPS-THUNB No. 8139 which bearing buds instead of flowers, since the flower orientation of 
<taxonomicName box="[1000,1145,401,425]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Lilium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolium">
<emphasis box="[1000,1145,401,425]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="173">L. lancifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will change from upwards to nod- ding with maturity as pedicels elongate (Y.D. Gao, pers. obs. in the field). In eastern Asia, there are very few species that have bulbils and heavy stem hair, facilitating the identifica- tion of the UPS-THUNB No. 8139 specimen. After extensive examination, we confirmed this specimen as one of Thunberg’s material of 
<taxonomicName box="[240,385,276,300]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Lilium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolium">
<emphasis box="[240,385,276,300]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="174">L. lancifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on possessing (1) trichomes on the stem and leaves (
<bibRefCitation author="Liang, S. Y. &amp; Tamura, M." box="[347,598,308,332]" editor="Wu, Z. Y." journalOrPublisher="Acta Phytotax. Sin" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" pagination="135 - 159" part="24" refString="Liang, S. Y. &amp; Tamura, M. 2000. Lilium L. Pp. 135 - 159 in: Wu, Z. Y. &amp; Raven, P. H. (eds.), Flora of China, vol. 24. Beijing: Science Press; St. Louis: Missouri Botanical Garden Press." title="Lilium L. Pp" type="journal article" volumeTitle="Flora of China" year="2000">Liang &amp; Tamura, 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Skinner, M. W." box="[609,759,308,332]" journalOrPublisher="New York, Oxford: Oxford University Press" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" pagination="172 - 193" refString="Skinner, M. W. 2002. Lilium. Pp. 172 - 193 in: Flora of North America Editorial Committee (eds.), Flora of North America north of Mexico, vol. 26. New York, Oxford: Oxford University Press." title="Lilium. Pp." type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Flora of North America Editorial Committee (eds.), Flora of North America north of Mexico, vol. 26" year="2002">Skinner, 2002</bibRefCitation>
) and (2) distal leaves bearing dark purple axillary bulbils (
<bibRefCitation author="Liang, S. Y. &amp; Tamura, M." editor="Wu, Z. Y." journalOrPublisher="Acta Phytotax. Sin" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" pagination="135 - 159" part="24" refString="Liang, S. Y. &amp; Tamura, M. 2000. Lilium L. Pp. 135 - 159 in: Wu, Z. Y. &amp; Raven, P. H. (eds.), Flora of China, vol. 24. Beijing: Science Press; St. Louis: Missouri Botanical Garden Press." title="Lilium L. Pp" type="journal article" volumeTitle="Flora of China" year="2000">Liang &amp; Tamura, 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Skinner, M. W." box="[309,459,370,394]" journalOrPublisher="New York, Oxford: Oxford University Press" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" pagination="172 - 193" refString="Skinner, M. W. 2002. Lilium. Pp. 172 - 193 in: Flora of North America Editorial Committee (eds.), Flora of North America north of Mexico, vol. 26. New York, Oxford: Oxford University Press." title="Lilium. Pp." type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Flora of North America Editorial Committee (eds.), Flora of North America north of Mexico, vol. 26" year="2002">Skinner, 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/400231/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" targetBox="[168,1149,543,1946]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph blockId="1.[1181,1476,544,594]" pageId="1" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1181,1232,545,565]" pageId="1" pageNumber="173">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
Thunberg's collection No. 8139 from Japan.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[123,766,183,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="174">
Typification of 
<taxonomicName box="[333,528,401,425]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Lilium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolium">
<emphasis box="[333,528,401,425]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="174">Lilium lancifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a first step towards resolution of the taxonomic and nomenclatural confusion of the species. Below, we designate the specimen UPS-THUNB No. 8139 as the lectotype of 
<taxonomicName authority="Thunberg" authorityName="Thunberg" box="[387,649,495,519]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Lilium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolium">
<emphasis box="[387,536,495,519]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="174">L. lancifolium</emphasis>
Thunberg
</taxonomicName>
, consistent with Art. 7–10 of the 
<emphasis box="[346,389,526,549]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="174">ICN</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J. &amp; Barrie, F. R. &amp; Buck, W. R. &amp; Demoulin, V &amp; Greuter, W. &amp; Hawksworth, D. L. &amp; Herendeen, P. S. &amp; Knapp, S. &amp; Marhold, K. &amp; Prado, J." box="[402,613,526,550]" journalOrPublisher="Konigstein: Koeltz Scientific Books" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" pagination="154" refString="McNeill, J., Barrie, F. R., Buck, W. R., Demoulin, V., Greuter, W., Hawksworth, D. L., Herendeen, P. S., Knapp, S., Marhold, K., Prado, J., Prud'homme, van Reine W. F., Smith, G. F., Wiersema, J. &amp; Turland, N. J. (eds.) 2012. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Regnum Vegetabile 154. Konigstein: Koeltz Scientific Books." title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Regnum Vegetabile" type="book chapter" year="2012">McNeill &amp; al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
). In particular, the specimen comprises an original collection of the species by the authority from the type locality (i.e., Japan), and satisfies the concept presented in the protologue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
